text: Protein J DOI 10.1007/s10930-015-9635-9 Expression, Crystallization and Preliminary X-ray Diffraction Analyses of Med-ORF10 in the Biosynthetic Pathway of an Antitumor Antibiotic Medermycin Yanli Liu1 Kashif Raﬁq Zahid1 Yi Yang3 (cid:2) Springer Science+Business Media New York 2015 Abstract Medermycin, as a prominent member of ben- zoisochromanequinones, possesses strong antitumor activ- ity and is biosynthesized under the control of a 29-ORF- containing biosynthetic gene cluster. Most of ORFs in this gene cluster have not been characterized, including a small protein encoding gene med-ORF10, proposed to play a regulatory role in biosynthesis of medermycin in an unknown mode. In this study, we reported the expression, protein preparation, crystallization and preliminary X-ray diffraction analyses of Med-ORF10 of the wild type Streptomyces strain. Firstly, we cloned and overexpressed med-ORF10 in Escherichia coli and puriﬁed the protein with 98 % purity and 3 mg/L yield. Then, we crystallized the protein at concentration of 20 mg/mL in condi- tion 22 % PEG 3350, 0.2 M magnesium formate and col- lected the data at 1.78 A˚ resolution. Finally, we detected the expression of Med-ORF10 in Streptomyces by western blotting. In conclusion, this study conﬁrmed the expression of Med-ORF10 protein in the wild-type strain of Strepto- myces AM-7161 and collected the X-ray diffraction data of Med-ORF10 crystal at 1.78 A˚ resolution. Keywords Med-ORF10 (cid:2) Gene cloning (cid:2) Expression and puriﬁcation (cid:2) Crystallization (cid:2) X-ray diffraction Abbreviations MED Medermycin ORF BIQ ACT GRA E. coli Escherichia coli Benzoisochromanequinones (BIQ) antibiotics, a group of bioactive aromatic polyketides, are produced by Strepto- myces [1] .Members of BIQ possess antibacterial, anti- cancer, anticoccidial or anti-platelet aggregation activities [1]. Prominent examples include medermycin (MED), actinorhodino (ACT), granaticin (GRA) and so on (Fig. 1a) [2, 3]. Medermycin (also known as lactoquinomycin), an antibiotic active against Gram-positive bacteria, was iso- lated from Streptomyces sp. K73 [4]. In addition to antibacterial activity, medermycin is also known as an anticancer agent [5–7]. Recent studies have shown that medermycin is a novel special inhibitor of serine/threonine kinase AKT/PKB, a central player in the signaling path- ways which plays a crucial role in human malignancies [8– 10]. The sequence study of medermycin biosynthetic gene Open reading frame Benzoisochromanequinones Actinorhodin Granaticin Fig. 1 BIQ antibiotics and med-ORF10 homologues in their gene clusters. a Chemical structures of representative BIQ antibiotics. b med-ORF10 homologues exist in the gene clusters of representative

cluster of Streptomyces sp. AM-7161 has shown that this gene cluster covers 29 Open Reading Frames (ORFs) (Fig. 1b) [11]. Extensive sequence comparison indicates the function of some med-ORFs. For example, med-ORF8 should be a glycosyltransferase responsible for C-glyco- sylation, med-ORF12 encodes a ketoreductase involved in the enantioselective reduction, and med-ORF13 encodes acyl carrier protein. med-ORF10 is a homologue of actVI- ORFA, a regulatory gene located in actinorhodin biosyn- thetic gene (act) cluster in Streptomyces coelicolor (Fig. 1b) [11–15]. We also identiﬁed homologues of med- ORF10 exist in other BIQ gene clusters, such as gra- ORF31 in gra cluster, implying that they may play a role in biosynthesis of BIQs (Fig. 1b). Sequence alignment shows that these proteins are highly conserved with similarity about 66 % (Fig. 1c), indicating that these proteins’ func- tion might be similar in the biosynthesis of BIQs. However, the exactly role of Med-ORF10 is not clear. To shed light on the biological function of medermycin biosynthetic gene med-ORF10, we sub cloned and BIQ antibiotics. c Sequence alignment of homologues of Med-ORF10 in medermycin biosynthetic gene cluster overexpressed the med-ORF10 in Escherichia coli. We tried to crystallize the puriﬁed protein and got the X-ray diffraction data at 1.78 A˚ resolution. Furthermore, we conﬁrmed the expression of Med-ORF10 in Streptomyces by using monoclonal antibody against Flag-tag to detect Flag-tagged-Med-ORF10 expression.

Streptomyces sp. AM7161 (AM-7161) is a wild type strain for medermycin production, while pIK340 is a plasmid containing medermycin biosynthetic gene cluster (kindly provided by Dr. Koji Ichinose) [11]. pIJ8600 is an inte- grative vector for expression of Streptomyces genes [16]. pET-28a (?) was used as a prokaryotic expression vector (kanamycin-resistant, Novagen). Escherichia coli BL21 (DE3) was used as host for Med-ORF10 expression. Expression, Crystallization and Preliminary X-ray Diffraction Analyses of Med-ORF10 in the… The full length coding sequence of med-ORF10 was cloned from pIK340 by PCR with primers speciﬁc for med- ORF10: forward: 50-ggaattccatatgtccacccaccgagtc-30, the reverse: 50- bold is cccaagcttcgattccggcaggtggtc-30, the bold is the restriction site for HindIII. Ampliﬁcation of med-ORF10 was carried out by 25 thermal cycles at 94 (cid:3)C for 1 min, at 65 (cid:3)C for 45 s, at 68 (cid:3)C for 1.5 min. PCR products were digested with NdeI/HindIII and ligated to the E. coli expression vector pET-28a (?) to produce His-tagged fusion protein. The recombinant plasmid was sequenced to conﬁrm the ﬁdelity of DNA ampliﬁcation. The resultant plasmid was named as pET28a-His-med-10.

To check native expression of Med-ORF10 in Strepto- myces cells, another pair of primers for PCR ampliﬁcation sense (50- of Flag-tagged-med-ORF10 was designed: ggaattccatatggattacaaggatgacgacgataagtccacccaccg-30, the bold for NdeI site; the underlined indicated for Flag tag sequence) and antisense (50-cgggatcctcacttatcgtcgtcatc- cttgtaatccgattccggc-30, the underlined indicated for Flag tag sequence). PCR ampliﬁ- cation was conducted under same conditions as above. The resultant PCR products were cloned into pIJ8600, resulting a plasmid pIJ8600-Flag-med-10. The recombinant plasmid pET28a-His-med-10 was trans- formed into competent cell of E. coli BL21 (DE3) and the cells were cultured overnight under selection of 50 lg/mL kanamycin. Then the overnight-cell cultures were trans- ferred into 2 L of 2 9 YT medium (16 g/L tryptone, 10 g/ L yeast extract and 5 g/L NaCl) with 50 lg/mL kanamycin for continuous cultivation at 37 (cid:3)C with shaking at 200 rpm. The cultured cells were induced with 0.25 mM b- D-1-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG) at an OD600 of 0.6 and cultured for 20 h at 15 (cid:3)C on a shaker at 180 rpm. The cells were harvested by centrifugation at 7000 rpm at 4 (cid:3)C for 10 min and stored in -80 (cid:3)C.

The frozen cell pellets (about 12.3 g/2L) were thawed and resuspended in 200 mL lysis buffer containing 20 mM Tris, pH 7.5, 500 mM NaCl, 5 mM b-mercaptoethanol (b- ME) and 5 % glycerol, and lysed by sonication at power 8.5, 10 min with 10 s on and 10 s off pulse. After soni- cation, the crude cell extract was centrifuged at 16 000 rpm at 4 (cid:3)C for 1 h. Then the supernatant was loaded to an open column with 4 mL Ni-nitrilotriacetate resin (Qiagen). After washing with 40 mL washing buffer (20 mM Tris, pH 7.5, the restriction site for NdeI; 1 M NaCl, 25 mM imidazole), His-tagged fusion protein was eluted by 15 mL elution buffer containing 20 mM Tris, pH 7.5, 250 mM NaCl, 250 mM imidazole. Protein was further puriﬁed by Superdex75 gel-ﬁltration (GE Healthcare, Piscataway, NJ) in the buffer (20 mM Tris, pH 7.5, 150 mM NaCl, 1 mM DTT). The crude protein as well as the puriﬁed protein were separated by SDS-PAGE and stained by bromophenol blue. For crystallization experi- ments, puriﬁed protein was concentrated to 20 mg/mL in a buffer containing 20 mM Tris, pH 7.5, 150 mM NaCl and 1 mM DTT using Amicon Ultra-15 Centrifugal Filter Units with a molecular weight 10 kDa (Millipore Corporation). 2.5 Protein Crystallization

Puriﬁed protein was crystallized using the sitting drop vapor diffusion method at 20 (cid:3)C by mixing 0.5 lL of the protein solution (20 mg/mL) with 0.5 lL of the reservoir solution. Initial crystals were obtained with a reservoir solution containing 20 % PEG 3350 and 0.2 M magnesium formate. After the initial condition was obtained, 24 types of optimized buffers with 6 PEG 3350 concentrations (16, 18, 20, 22, 24, 26 %) and 4 magnesium formate concen- trations (0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.4 M) were prepared. For opti- mization of crystallization condition, puriﬁed protein was crystallized using the same method by mixing 1 lL of the protein solution (20 mg/mL) with 1 lL of the optimized buffer. Finally, the best crystals were obtained with a reservoir solution containing 22 % PEG 3350, 0.2 M magnesium formate. Before ﬂash-freezing crystals in liquid nitrogen, crystals were soaked in a cryoprotectant con- sisting of 85 % reservoir solution and 15 % glycerol. 2.6 X-ray Diffraction and Data Collection X-ray diffraction data for His-tagged fusion Med-ORF10 were collected at 100 K at beamline19 ID of Advanced Photon Source (APS), Argonne National Laboratory and all the data sets were processed using the HKL-3000 suite [17]. 2.7 Expression Detection of Med-ORF10 in its

The pIJ8600-Flag-med-10 plasmid was transformed into its native wild type strain Streptomyces sp. AM-7161 by protoplast transformation [16].Total proteins were extrac- ted from 5-day culture of AM-7161/pIJ8600-Flag-med-10 in R4 medium [16, 18]: 500 lL of AM-7161 spores were inoculated into R4 medium and cultivated for 5 days at 30 (cid:3)C on a shaker (200 rpm) by using thiostrepton (12.5 lg/mL) to induce the fusion protein expression. The harvested cell pellets were lysed and extracted as the reported procedures [16, 18]. SDS-PAGE and western blotting were performed to detect the expression of Med- ORF10 by using monoclonal antibody against Flag tag as the primary antibody. 3.1 Protein Expression and Puriﬁcation To test the expression condition of His-tagged-Med- ORF10, we performed the small scale expression test and found that the fusion protein was expressed in E. coli BL21 (DE3) under induced conditions of 0.25 mM IPTG for 20 h at 15 (cid:3)C (Fig. 2). The SDS-PAGE showed a clear induced protein band at molecular weight about 20 kDa, which was consistent with the predicted molecular weight 20.406 kDa of the His-tagged fusion protein (http://web.expasy.org/ protparam/) (Fig. 2, lane 2). To obtain enough protein sample for crystallization, frozen cell pellets from 2 liters of cell culture were lysed by sonication. The His-tagged fusion protein was extracted from the whole cell-soluble-protein portion by afﬁnity chromatography on Ni-nitrilotriacetate resin (Qiagen).

We further puriﬁed the fusion protein by gel ﬁltration and obtained a yield about 3 mg recombinant Med-ORF10 fusion protein from 1 liter cell culture (a recovery of 3 mg/6.2 g wet weight cells) with purity about 98 % (Fig. 3, lane 2). 3.2 Protein Crystallization and X-ray Diffraction

After 10 days of tiny crystals were obtained in the reservoir solution containing 20 % PEG 3350, 0.2 M magnesium formate. However these crystals were not big enough for data collection, so we optimized the crystallization conditions by changing the buffer concentrations. After another 10 days waiting, we obtained satisfactory crystals from the reservoir solution containing 22 % PEG 3350, 0.2 M magnesium formate (Fig. 4) and collected the data at 1.78 A˚ resolution at beam line 19 ID of the Advanced Photon Source at Argonne National Laboratory (Argonne, IL) (Fig. 5). We successfully detected the expression of Med-ORF10 in the transformed strain by using the monoclonal antibody (Biyuntian Ltd, Beijing) against Flag-tag (Fig. 6). These data indicates that this gene could express in its native strain, implying it should play some role in medermycin biosynthesis. is well known that Streptomyces antibiotics were It biosynthesized under the control of a complex regulatory system in vivo [3, 16, 18, 19]. So far, many types of reg- ulatory factors involving the antibiotic production via dif- ferent modes have been identiﬁed, including global regulators and pathway-speciﬁc regulators.

In the biosynthetic pathways of BIQ family, many type of regulatory genes were identiﬁed, such as well-studied actII-ORF4, which encodes a protein belonging to the family of SARP (Streptomyces antibiotic regulatory pro- tein, SARP) [3]. ActII-ORF4 was found to be located on the gene cluster of actinorhodin and regulated expression of many genes in the same cluster by binding to its target promoters [3, 18]. Another gene playing a regulatory role in actinorhodin pathway was actVI-ORFA, which encodes a small protein [14]. Similarly, the function of Med-ORF10, a homologue of ActVI-ORFA found in the medermycin biosynthetic pathway, is still unknown.

In the present work, we successfully expressed Med- ORF10 in E. coli and obtained crystals good enough for later structure determination. Unfortunately, we could not obtain selenomethionine-substituted crystals; especially we could not ﬁnd any model for its structure determination. However, this initial crystal information will set light for the structural and functional determinations in the future. On the other hand, we conﬁrmed the expression of Med- ORF10 in Streptomyces by using monoclonal antibody detect Flag-tagged-Med-ORF10 against Flag-tag the expression. Western blotting analyses showed that fused protein could be expressed normally with expected molecular weight in Streptomyces native cells. In summary, our data supported that this unknown protein Med-ORF10 could be expressed in E. coli and Streptomyce strains, implying it should play some role in medermycin biosynthesis. We also crystallized it under certain conditions and collected diffraction data at 1.78 A˚ resolution for later structural and functional characteriza- tions. These studies provide evidences for the functional Med-ORF10 protein in Streptomyces strains and facilitate our further investigation.
